{"active_answer": "the prevention of escape", "active_index": 18, "active_question": "According to Takashi Tsujimura, what was the primary object of hojonawa (capture rope)?", "audit_index": 1, "decision": "drop", "document_sha256": "ae2e1262a20609f15627ff379d1ab7f7c95f1e57ed6bdb634d53b935b7af614d", "fact_id": "fact-c0cc30ba0b937b0f11f1", "projection_lineage": {"active_index": 18, "baseline_rows": 540, "baseline_sha256": "3178dc973f017cb4820223ecbb2a772faa072fc2eddb80fb54b23091f7034b24", "prior_context_merit_review": true}, "reason": "The same attributed answer is already retained in a more informative question contrasting restraint with kinbaku's aesthetic aim.", "reason_code": "duplicate_hojojutsu_escape_purpose", "review_pass": "semantic_redundancy_and_resource_naturalness_reaudit", "reviewed_at": "2026-07-14", "reviewer": "codex-context-merit-audit-v57", "risk_features": {"answer_tokens": 4, "bare_answer_points": 2, "named_person_trivia_points": 0, "pronoun_count": 0, "question_tokens": 13, "risk_score": 2, "short_question_points": 0}, "schema": "context-merit-audit-v57", "source": "kinbakutoday", "source_document": "data/raw/kinbakutoday_cbbff84b319d0813.json", "source_document_file_sha256": "e4c42b7599350c955ef1d3517b80b09e51d8f43f6cc028498c47ad3af8802ad4", "source_support": "normalized_extractive", "support_evidence": "In a 1953 article, Takashi Tsujimura, writing about tying the takate kote distinguished between hojojutsu and kinbaku based on aesthetics. He wrote: “Various methods for applying hojonawa (capture rope) have been left behind in writing, but since these make the prevention of escape their primary object, even if they may be useful as reference, it is only natural that they differ from tying methods whose purpose is the pursuit of the aesthetic beauty of kinbaku.”", "support_evidence_sha256": "25211a8c2be9e22aed3db8537d4c11257f10027a34ddf25c1c3c4ac900cdfed5", "url": "https://www.kinbakutoday.com/exploring-the-origins-of-kinbaku/"}
{"active_answer": "edge play", "active_index": 53, "active_question": "How does Anatomie Studio classify suspension in its studio safety rules?", "audit_index": 2, "decision": "keep", "document_sha256": "1d66ad91809311443abe27e549840e5436c510a1e66fe1e2cefd6d68c078d3c4", "fact_id": "fact-eb477d063e72bae0adb8", "projection_lineage": {"active_index": 53, "baseline_rows": 540, "baseline_sha256": "3178dc973f017cb4820223ecbb2a772faa072fc2eddb80fb54b23091f7034b24", "prior_context_merit_review": true}, "reason": "The studio-attributed classification is concise safety context and is clearer than the redundant generic term lookup removed in this tranche.", "reason_code": "retain_clear_studio_suspension_classification", "review_pass": "semantic_redundancy_and_resource_naturalness_reaudit", "reviewed_at": "2026-07-14", "reviewer": "codex-context-merit-audit-v57", "risk_features": {"answer_tokens": 2, "bare_answer_points": 5, "named_person_trivia_points": 0, "pronoun_count": 1, "question_tokens": 11, "risk_score": 8, "short_question_points": 0}, "schema": "context-merit-audit-v57", "source": "anatomiestudio", "source_document": "data/raw/anatomiestudio_27ecdd4d7c9a5560.json", "source_document_file_sha256": "1f968e0d0b2428eab259dfd3c291f58483c5384b6eebca1fa2505ce9b39f23af", "source_support": "normalized_extractive", "support_evidence": "Use of the points is reserved for experienced people. If you see people suspending, they have very likely completed our courses or have received tuition here or elsewhere. Suspension is edge play. It is risky. Do not endanger yourself or others by suspending before you are ready. Respect when the owners or staff ask you to stop suspending. Come ask us about classes if you’d like to learn!", "support_evidence_sha256": "a07e00f26e2cb3814f406f168cf8d5ae46070d72a782ccc3286915f45d455022", "url": "https://www.anatomiestudio.com/etiquette-and-consent"}
{"active_answer": "edge play", "active_index": 328, "active_question": "What specific term is used to describe rope suspension because it is inherently dangerous?", "audit_index": 3, "decision": "drop", "document_sha256": "0d28c9418178793f14c52665b6765d06326a68abe78dc9c5e3f4e44b82c03a63", "fact_id": "fact-ba0bcde9e13c55a82239", "projection_lineage": {"active_index": 328, "baseline_rows": 540, "baseline_sha256": "3178dc973f017cb4820223ecbb2a772faa072fc2eddb80fb54b23091f7034b24", "prior_context_merit_review": true}, "reason": "The one-word term lookup duplicates the clearer Anatomie Studio classification retained in this tranche; the longer ESINEM account remains represented by other substantive facts.", "reason_code": "duplicate_edge_play_term_lookup", "review_pass": "semantic_redundancy_and_resource_naturalness_reaudit", "reviewed_at": "2026-07-14", "reviewer": "codex-context-merit-audit-v57", "risk_features": {"answer_tokens": 2, "bare_answer_points": 5, "named_person_trivia_points": 0, "pronoun_count": 1, "question_tokens": 14, "risk_score": 8, "short_question_points": 0}, "schema": "context-merit-audit-v57", "source": "esinem", "source_document": "data/raw/esinem_77368ccdc66acad0.json", "source_document_file_sha256": "f5f1b9c35c4a982db69d1a2651d9f6ec8e28e76b8715648e85aa6d1e9fa2d05f", "source_support": "normalized_extractive", "support_evidence": "Rope performance and rope photography is often one of those tricky arts that makes suspension look like a breeze. Don’t get me wrong, suspension can be straightforward and painless and lovely, but in my experience, in performance rope this is rarely the case. Bottoming in rope, particularly in suspension, is not something that I take lightly. Rope suspension falls under the term “edge play” because it is inherently dangerous. It is risky play in that there are real possibilities for injury to occur. Overextension, muscle tears, circulation problems and nerve compression and damage can and do happen; sometimes with lasting repercussions. All suspension bottoms (should!) go into suspension knowing these risks. I do. And the tops that tie me would not tie me if I didn’t. There is responsibility taken on both sides of the equation.", "support_evidence_sha256": "c59517193549504f0948a45a8ade47eafb43f83982e03a0597f3ef3753c29007", "url": "https://www.esinem.com/on-rope-performance-reactions/"}
{"active_answer": "“How does my body feel?” and “In what emotional state am I?”", "active_index": 479, "active_question": "Which two self-scan questions does Rope365 suggest asking before tying or being tied?", "audit_index": 4, "decision": "drop", "document_sha256": "ba41f96db0578f593930a21a579f6a30f3658b100da8390fea2edbdf5b4abb3d", "fact_id": "fact-64a4807147c057265799", "projection_lineage": {"active_index": 479, "baseline_rows": 540, "baseline_sha256": "3178dc973f017cb4820223ecbb2a772faa072fc2eddb80fb54b23091f7034b24", "prior_context_merit_review": true}, "reason": "An earlier edited row already asks the same two Rope365 readiness questions and includes the same answer with only an introductory phrase added.", "reason_code": "duplicate_pre_scene_self_scan", "review_pass": "semantic_redundancy_and_resource_naturalness_reaudit", "reviewed_at": "2026-07-14", "reviewer": "codex-context-merit-audit-v57", "risk_features": {"answer_tokens": 12, "bare_answer_points": 0, "named_person_trivia_points": 0, "pronoun_count": 0, "question_tokens": 13, "risk_score": 0, "short_question_points": 0}, "schema": "context-merit-audit-v57", "source": "rope365", "source_document": "data/raw/rope_resources_v1/rope365__b602b6493b5eb6f55206.json", "source_document_file_sha256": "1fc5d27338c2dde3484df8566863c6dc6f855905a5915882b642b02faaa4620d", "source_support": "normalized_extractive", "support_evidence": "Having a ‘date’ to meet a fellow rope lover and do some tying together is usually something to look forward to. But let’s be honest, some days are better than others. It might be a good idea to do an honest ‘self-scan’ about how you’re doing today, before you start to tie or be tied. Ask yourself: “How does my body feel?” and “In what emotional state am I?” Then translate it to the situation of starting to use rope, and ask yourself: “What can I give or receive, right now?”.", "support_evidence_sha256": "421a7cffc087043d6fdcd4b09892813443602c2c33e198a0c98a064e0183281a", "url": "https://rope365.com/communication/"}
